<article>
    <h1>New on K-pop, J-pop playlist</h1>
    <h2></h2>
    <section>
        <a href="/singapore/the-straits-times/textview" title="The Straits Times">The Straits Times</a>
        - <a href="/singapore/the-straits-times/20201008/textview" title="The Straits Times - 2020-10-08"><time>2020-10-08</time></a>
        - <span>LIFE MUSIC</span>
        - <span role="byline">Jan Lee</span>
    </section>

    <p>Both new young artists and es­tab­lished acts in the K-pop and J-pop world dropped new works in the past month. The Straits Times high­lights 10 re­leases.</p>
    <p>jan­lee@sph.com.sg</p>
    <p>1 POP</p>
    <p>WHEN­EVER YOU CALL</p>
    <p>Arashi</p>
    <p>Hear it on: Spo­tify, Ap­ple Mu­sic and other mu­sic stream­ing plat­forms</p>
    <p>Watch it on: bit.ly/3d3JcDm</p>
    <p>Vet­eran J-pop boy band Arashi, who are go­ing on an in­def­i­nite hia­tus at the end of this year af­ter 21 years, have re­leased their first fully English sin­gle in a bid to bring their mu­sic to a more in­ter­na­tional au­di­ence.</p>
    <p>When­ever You Call is co-pro­duced by Grammy-win­ning Amer­i­can singer Bruno Mars. The ro­man­tic bal­lad is ded­i­cated to fans, with the band promis­ing them un­chang­ing love.</p>
    <p>2 POP ROCK TURN OVER?</p>
    <p>Mr Chil­dren</p>
    <p>Hear it on: Spo­tify, Ap­ple Mu­sic and other mu­sic stream­ing plat­forms</p>
    <p>Ja­panese pop-rock band Mr Chil­dren are one of the best-sell­ing acts in their home coun­try.</p>
    <p>Their lat­est sin­gle is the theme song for the drama Love Will Be­gin When Money Ends, the late Haruma Miura’s last tele­vi­sion work. Ac­com­pa­nied by prom­i­nent gui­tar sounds, it makes for a com­fort­ing lis­ten.</p>
    <p>3 R&B UM­BRELLA</p>
    <p>H&D</p>
    <p>Hear it on: Spo­tify, Ap­ple Mu­sic and other mu­sic stream­ing plat­forms</p>
    <p>Watch it on: bit.ly/33yCimm</p>
    <p>K-pop singers Lee Han-gyul, 20, and Nam Do-hyon, 15 – who form the duo H&D – may be young, but the con­fi­dent way they sing and rap their way through their new song Um­brella shows ma­tu­rity.</p>
    <p>Nam’s laid­back style of rap­ping and Lee’s sen­sual vo­cals com­ple­ment each other su­perbly. 4</p>
    <p>POP HEARD THAT THERE’S GOOD PASTA</p>
    <p>Aimyon</p>
    <p>Hear it on: Spo­tify, Ap­ple Mu­sic and other mu­sic stream­ing plat­forms Watch it on: bit.ly/3iBnbx1</p>
    <p>Ja­panese singer-song­writer Aimyon, 25, has been a hit in her home coun­try, es­pe­cially since her chart-top­ping 2018 sin­gle Marigold.</p>
    <p>In her third album, Heard That There’s Good Pasta, fans can still find the heart­felt and pow­er­ful songs Aimyon is known for, such as Harunohi (Spring Day) and Naked Heart.</p>
    <p>But check out Cig­a­rette, in which the star adopts a cuter way of singing. The rock-in­flu­enced Marsh­mal­low show­cases her range as well.</p>
    <p>5 HIP-HOP HEART­BREAK HO­TEL</p>
    <p>Geeks fea­tur­ing DeVita</p>
    <p>Hear it on: Spo­tify, Ap­ple Mu­sic and other mu­sic stream­ing plat­forms Watch it on: bit.ly/3jCQH6J</p>
    <p>South Korean hip-hop duo Geeks have teamed up with vo­cal­ist DeVita for a track that deals with in­fi­delity.</p>
    <p>DeVita, also from South Korea, show­cases her dis­tinc­tive vo­cals but it is Lil Boi and Louie’s ir­rev­er­ent, boy­ish rap­ping that steals the show.</p>
    <p>6 ORIG­I­NAL SOUND­TRACK MY LOVE</p>
    <p>Jo Yuri (Iz*One)</p>
    <p>Hear it on: Spo­tify, Ap­ple Mu­sic and other mu­sic stream­ing plat­forms Watch it on: bit.ly/2FaCrDq</p>
    <p>Yuri, a mem­ber of K-pop girl group Iz*One, lends her voice to the sound­track of the clas­si­cal mu­sic-themed ro­mance drama Do You Like Brahms (2020)?</p>
    <p>Her voice and the song both have a sooth­ing, cafe-mu­sic qual­ity. The clean in­stru­men­tals and Yuri’s sweet vo­cals make this song a de­par­ture from the slow, pow­er­ful bal­lads K-dra­mas tend to favour.</p>
    <p>7 PSY­CHE­DELIC POP YAYOU HOI</p>
    <p>Sogumm and Oh Hyuk</p>
    <p>Hear it on: Spo­tify, Ap­ple Mu­sic and other mu­sic stream­ing plat­forms Watch it on: bit.ly/33C895M</p>
    <p>South Korean singer-song­writer Sogumm pairs up with Oh Hyuk, the lead singer of in­die band Hyukoh, for this trippy, psy­che­delic track.</p>
    <p>The mu­sic video is equally bizarre, with the two artists en­ter­ing an artsy jun­gle from a non­de­script door.</p>
    <p>8 POP THE ALBUM</p>
    <p>Black­pink</p>
    <p>Hear it on: Spo­tify, Ap­ple Mu­sic and other mu­sic stream­ing plat­forms</p>
    <p>Watch it on: bit.ly/36Dv8PY</p>
    <p>K-pop quar­tet Black­pink have fi­nally re­leased their first full-length Korean-lan­guage album since their de­but in 2016.</p>
    <p>Aside from Ice Cream, which was re­leased ear­lier this year and which fea­tures Amer­i­can singer Se­lena Gomez, the album also sees the girl group col­lab­o­rat­ing with rap­per Cardi B on a sexy track, Bet You Wanna.</p>
    <p>The lead sin­gle is the dance an­them Lovesick Girls and the girls show off their moves in a slickly pro­duced mu­sic video.</p>
    <p>9 HIP-HOP/POP LET IT SHINE</p>
    <p>Pre­cious</p>
    <p>Hear it on: Spo­tify, Ap­ple Mu­sic and other mu­sic stream­ing plat­forms Watch it on: bit.ly/30Ed­szS</p>
    <p>The new five-mem­ber K-pop girl group Pre­cious have an im­pres­sive de­but album.</p>
    <p>Let It Shine es­chews the cute bub­blegum route many girl groups take and in­stead opts for the un­abashedly hard hip-hop track Bebe as the lead sin­gle.</p>
    <p>The track is boosted by rap­per Han-woom’s speedy raps and con­fi­dent per­for­mance as well as the group’s strong dance chore­og­ra­phy.</p>
    <p>10</p>
    <p>TECHNOPOP</p>
    <p>TIME WARP</p>
    <p>Per­fume</p>
    <p>Hear it on:</p>
    <p>Spo­tify, Ap­ple Mu­sic and other mu­sic stream­ing plat­forms</p>
    <p>Watch it on: bit.ly/36IFb62</p>
    <p>Ja­panese technopop group Per­fume’s lat­est track re­tains the trio’s es­tab­lished style of elec­tronic dance-pop with heavy au­to­tune.</p>
    <p>In line with the song’s ti­tle, their first sin­gle in two years has a stun­ning and colour­ful mu­sic video that rewinds and fast-for­wards.</p>

